"content": "<style>\nh1.thlex-title { font-size: 1.3em; margin: 0 0 0.4em; }\n.thlex-key { color: #888; font-size: 0.85em; font-weight: normal; margin-right: 0.4em; }\nnav.thlex-index { margin: 0.5em 0 0.75em; }\nnav.thlex-index ul { margin: 0; padding-left: 1.2em; }\nnav.thlex-index li { margin: 0.15em 0; font-size: 0.95em; }\n.thlex-section { margin: 0.6em 0; }\nh2.thlex-heading { font-size: 1em; margin: 0.5em 0 0.2em; }\nh3.thlex-subheading { font-size: 0.95em; font-weight: normal; font-style: italic; margin: 0.2em 0; }\n.thlex-language-sets { margin: 0.3em 0 0.3em 1em; }\n.thlex-language-set { margin: 0.4em 0; padding-left: 0.75em; border-left: 3px solid #e0e0e0; }\n.thlex-language { font-size: 0.8em; color: #888; margin-right: 0.4em; }\n.thlex-lemma { font-weight: bold; font-family: serif; }\n.thlex-translit { color: #555; font-style: italic; font-size: 0.9em; margin-left: 0.3em; }\n.thlex-refs { font-size: 0.85em; color: #444; margin-top: 0.15em; }\n.thlex-paragraphs p { margin: 0.35em 0; font-size: 0.95em; line-height: 1.5; }\n.thlex-image { margin: 0.5em 0; display: block; }\n.thlex-image img { max-width: 100%; height: auto; display: block; }\nfigcaption.thlex-caption { font-size: 0.85em; color: #555; font-style: italic; margin-top: 0.2em; }\n.thlex-abbr { border-bottom: 1px dotted #888; cursor: help; }\n.thlex-xref { color: #1a5fb4; }\nspan[data-bnType=\"bibleReference\"] { color: #1a5fb4; }\ntable.thlex-table { border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 0.9em; margin: 0.5em 0; }\ntable.thlex-table td { padding: 0.2em 0.6em; vertical-align: top; border: 1px solid #ddd; }\ntable.thlex-table tr:first-child td { font-weight: bold; background: #f5f5f5; }\nul.thlex-index-list { margin: 0.4em 0; padding-left: 1.4em; font-size: 0.95em; line-height: 1.6; }\nul.thlex-index-list ul { margin: 0.1em 0; padding-left: 1.4em; }\n.thlex-index-key { font-weight: bold; font-style: italic; }\n</style><h1 class=\"thlex-title\" id=\"FAUNA:6.11\"><span class=\"thlex-key\">6.11</span> Scorpion</h1><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">References:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-sets\">\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Hebrew</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">עַקְרָב</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(‘aqrav)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Num34:4\">NUM 34:4</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Deut8:15\">DEU 8:15</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Josh15:3\">JOS 15:3</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Judg1:36\">JDG 1:36</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Kgs12:11\">1KI 12:11</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Kgs12:14\">1KI 12:14</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Chr10:11\">2CH 10:11</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Chr10:14\">2CH 10:14</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezek2:6\">EZK 2:6</a></div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Greek</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">σκορπίος</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(scorpios)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Luke10:19\">LUK 10:19</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Luke11:12\">LUK 11:12</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Rev9:3\">REV 9:3</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Rev9:5\">REV 9:5</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Rev9:10\">REV 9:10</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Sir26:7\">SIR 26:7</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Sir39:30\">SIR 39:30</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/4Macc11:10\">4MA 11:10</a></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">Discussion:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-paragraphs\">\n<p><figure class=\"thlex-image\"><img class=\"thlex-img\" src=\"images/WEB-0793_scorpion.jpg\" alt=\"Scorpion\"><figcaption class=\"thlex-caption\">Scorpion (© אבי בן זקן (https://www.flickr.com/photos/evilmacro/) (Wikimedia Commons))</figcaption></figure>There is complete agreement that these words refer to the scorpion. Many scholars accept that <em>‘aqrav</em> was also a nickname for a type of whip used for punishing criminals.</p>\n</div>\n</div><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">Description:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-paragraphs\">\n<p>The scorpion is an eight-legged creature. In the land of Israel it grows to about 13 centimeters (5 inches) long, but in some tropical countries scorpions can be up to 18 centimeters (7 inches) long. The front pair of legs has claws similar to those on a crab, and the tail, which it can arch over its head, carries a fierce sting. It feeds on other insects and on small reptiles, such as baby lizards. It grasps its prey in its claws and stings it with its tail, either killing it or paralyzing it.</p>\n</div>\n</div><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">Special significance or symbolism:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-paragraphs\">\n<p>In the Hebrew Bible the scorpion epitomizes harsh, inhospitable living conditions.</p>\n</div>\n</div><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">Translation:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-paragraphs\">\n<p>The passages in 1Kings and 2Chronicles probably refer to a particularly painful type of whip, hence the <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"New English Bible (1970)\">NEB</abbr> use of “lash&quot;, <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Jerusalem Bible (1966)\">JB</abbr> “loaded scourge&quot;, and <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Today&#x27;s English Version (Good News Bible)\">TEV</abbr> “bullwhips&quot;. A phrase such as “scorpion whip” is used in many non-English translations.</p>\n<p>In <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Num34:4\">NUM 34:4</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Josh15:3\">JOS 15:3</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Judg1:36\">JDG 1:36</a> reference is made to a place called <em>ma‘aleh ‘aqrabim</em> “Scorpion Pass&quot;, but since place names are usually not translated, the name Akrabbim Pass is usually used in translation.</p>\n<p>Scorpions are found almost worldwide, except in the Arctic tundra and on some islands. In most places, therefore, a local word will be available.</p>\n</div>\n</div>",
